    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div type="letter">
                <div type="text">
                    <opener>
                        <placeName>Edinburgh</placeName>
                        <date>Dec<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. 7<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. 1875</date>
                        <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                    </opener>
                    <div type="transcription">
                        <p>May I beg the addition of your name to the enclosed application. M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Croll suggests that you might be willing perhaps to head the “General Knowledge” column.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> If you do so you will greatly gratify him and do a service to one who I am sure is deserving of the honour.</p>
                        <p>Yours very truly | Arch Geikie <lb/> <lb/></p>
                        <p rend="left">Charles Darwin Esq</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                
            </div>
            
            
            <div type="footnotes">
                <note xml:id="foot.f1">CD recommended <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1127.xml">James Croll</ref> for fellowship of the Royal Society of London from general knowledge (The Royal Society archive GB 117, EC/1876/08). Croll was elected a fellow of the society in June 1876 (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6563.xml"><hi rend="italic">Record of the Royal Society of London</hi></ref>). See also <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 23, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10291.xml">letter to Archibald Geikie, 9 December 1875</ref>.</note>
                </div>
        
